ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM-BACKGROUND
The Accidental Release Prevention (ARP) requirements mandated in Section 112 (r) of the 1990 Clean Air Act (CAA) Amendments were promulgated by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) on June 20, 1996. The requirements are codified in 40 CFR 68, Subparts A  H. Under the ARP Program, a facility that has more than a threshold quantity of a regulated substance in a process must comply with the requirements of the ARP provisions.
The List Rule (under 40 CFR 68, Subpart C, and Tables 1 through 4 of 68.130) identifies regulated substance threshold quantities for determining ARP Program applicability. Threshold quantities have been established for flammable and toxic substances. The threshold quantity for all regulated flammables (Table 3 of the regulation) is 10,000 pounds. The threshold determination for mixtures of flammable substances is in accordance with 40 CFR 68.115(b) (2). In cases where the listed substance is greater than one percent by weight of the mixture (for a flammable), the entire weight of the mixture is considered in the threshold determination, unless it can be demonstrated that the mixture itself does not hav

The Energy Transfer Gulf Coast NGL,  Mont Belvieu North/Central Storage Facility (hereinafter referred to as Stationary Source) is a Program 3 process under the ARP Program based on the following criteria:
	The Stationary Source stores greater than the threshold quantities of regulated substances,
	A worst case release of a regulated substance would affect public receptors, and
	It is a manned facility that is subject to OSHA PSM regulation.
This report documents the steps taken to determine the program applicability and develop the Risk Management Plan (RMP) for the Stationary Source. These steps include:
	Verification of program applicability;
	Verification of chemical quantities in each process and largest vessel quantity;
	Completion of the off site consequence analysis and impacts; and
	Update of the five year accident history
The Stationary Source is a Storage and Transfer Terminal. Butane, Propane, Isobutane, Ethylene, and Ethyl Mercaptan are the Accidental Release Prevention (ARP)  regulated flammable substances that are present at the Stationary Source.
This is a 5-year review and update of the hazard assessment for the Stationary Source, as required by 40 CFR Subpart B §68.20. 
This report documents the steps taken to confirm the program applicability and conduct the Hazard Assessment for the Risk Management Plan (RMP) filing for the Stationary Source. These steps include:
·	Verification of program applicability;
·	Review and update of chemical quantities in each process and largest vessel quantity;
·	Review and update of the off-site consequence analysis and impacts;
·	Update and re-validate PHA;
·	Verification that refresher training of operating procedures has been completed;
·	Verification of adequacy and implementation of compliance audits for procedures and practices;
·	Verification that maintenance/mechanical integrity has been inspected and tested;
·	Verification that annual certifications of operating procedures are current and accurate;
